> Ras-el-Hanout is a spice mixture used throughout North Africa. Literally translated, the name means 'top of the shop'. Kind of like our 'top drawer' - the best each spice seller has to offer. No two merchants have quite the same blend but ours contains chillies, rose petals and ginger amongst other deliciously fragrant things. It brings fabulous aromas and flavours to this stew. Enjoy!

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When the oil is hot, add the @British beef mince{250%g}. Break up the beef with a #wooden spoon{} and season it with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Cook until nicely brown, continuing to break it up with your spoon, ~{6-7%minutes}.

Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1}(peeled and chopped into roughly 1cm pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, then remove the core from the @red pepper{1}(halved and deseeded) and thinly slice. Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}(sliced into 1cm wide rounds). Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Once the beef has browned, add the onion, pepper and @ras-el-hanout{1%tsp}. Stir together and cook for ~{5%minutes}. Add the garlic, stir and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Pour the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} and @water{200%ml} into the pan with the @beef stock pot{1}. Bring to the boil, and stir to dissolve the stock pot, then reduce the heat to medium-low. Leave the stew to simmer for ~{20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, boil your #kettle{}. Put the @couscous{150%g} in a #mixing bowl{}. Add a drizzle of oil and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{}(grind). Pour the @water for the couscous{300%ml}(boiling) into your bowl of couscous and cover with #clingfilm{} or a #plate{} and leave for ~{10%minutes}.

Heat another frying pan over medium heat (no oil). Add the @flaked almonds{25%g} and toast until golden brown, about ~{3%minutes}. When done, remove them from the pan.

> TIP: Watch the almonds like a hawk, they burn very easily!

Once the almonds are out of the pan, increase the heat to high. Cook the courgette without oil, ~{5%minutes} on each side. Once nicely charred, transfer to a plate, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and set aside.

Season the stew to taste with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, then stir through the coriander. Fluff up the couscous and divide between #bowls{}, spoon over the beef stew and finish with some charred courgettes and a sprinkling of flaked almonds. Enjoy!